          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">5,000+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Valid RE- words</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">6 tiles</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">R tiles in bag</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Front-Hooking with RE — The Board Extension Play</h2>

      <p>RE- is the king of front-hooks. Almost any verb on the board can be extended with RE- in front, and because R and E are so common, you'll almost always have the option available.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 RE- Front-Hook Goldmine</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Every verb your opponent plays is a potential target. <span class="text-white font-medium">PLAY → REPLAY</span>, <span class="text-white font-medium">LOAD → RELOAD</span>, <span class="text-white font-medium">FILL → REFILL</span>. You invest just 2 points (R+E) but score the entire extended word. If the extension reaches a Triple Word Score, you've turned their 8-point word into your 30+ point play.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">PLAY → REPLAY</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">11 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">LOAD → RELOAD</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">7 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">FILL → REFILL</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">9 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">STOCK → RESTOCK</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">13 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">MAKE → REMAKE</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">12 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">BUILD → REBUILD</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">10 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">COUNT → RECOUNT</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">9 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">CYCLE → RECYCLE</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">14 pts</span>
        </span>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">RE- Bingo Strategy — Consistent 50-Point Plays</h2>

      <p>RE- is statistically the most common bingo prefix because R and E are drawn so frequently. When you hold R, E, and five other tiles with a recognizable verb root, you're sitting on a bingo.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">RE + 5</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Letters needed for bingo</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">~15%</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Of bingos use RE-</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">12 tiles</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">R+E combined in bag</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>Top RE- bingo words to memorize: RETRACE, RESTFUL, REVISED, RECOUNT, RELATED, RETURNS, REFUSED, and RESPECT. These all use common tiles, making them highly achievable.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy — When to Hold RE</h2>

      <p>Because R and E are so common, the decision to hold them is different from rarer prefixes. You'll draw RE combinations frequently, so the opportunity cost of holding is lower.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Hold RE aggressively:</span> Unlike scarcer prefixes, RE tiles will reappear if you play them. But when your other 5 tiles form a clear verb (TRACE, BUILD, COUNT, STOCK), absolutely hold for the bingo — the 50-point bonus far outweighs an extra turn or two of lower scores.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Look for board hooks first:</span> Before holding for a bingo, check if any word on the board accepts RE- in front. An immediate 12-15 point hook play may be better than speculating on a bingo that requires a specific board opening.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Don't over-hold:</span> Because RE is just 2 points, it's tempting to always keep it. But if your other tiles are poor (too many vowels, duplicate consonants), play the R or E independently to improve your rack balance on the next draw.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Combine with back-hooks:</span> RE- words often accept -ED, -ER, or -ING at the end. REWORK → REWORKED (8 letters). If you spot a RE- + suffix combination using all 7 tiles, that's your bingo path — even if it uses 8 tiles through an existing letter on the board.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Summary</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🎯 Summary</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">RE- is the <span class="text-white font-medium">most frequently playable prefix</span> in Scrabble thanks to the abundance of R and E tiles. With 5,000+ valid words, universal verb hookability, and the highest bingo frequency of any prefix, RE- should be a cornerstone of your strategy. Scan every board for hookable verbs, hold RE when your remaining tiles form a word, and remember that this 2-point investment regularly generates 50+ point returns.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Related Articles -->
      <aside class="border-t border-gray-800 mt-12 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
        <div class="grid gap-3">
